Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.640
&gt;&gt; Hello, and welcome to another Authors at
Google Talk coming to you from Irvine, California.

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:12.780
Today, we are welcoming Hal Niedzviecki. Hal
is the founder of Broken Pencil magazine and

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:18.630
has published numerous works of social commentary
and fiction including: Hello, I'm Special:

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:24.160
How Individuality Became the New Conformity,
and We Want Some Too: Underground Desire and

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:29.619
the Reinvention of Mass Culture. Follow Hal
on his blog, The Peep Diaries. Welcome, Hal.

00:00:29.619 --> 00:00:36.700
&gt;&gt; NIEDZVIECKI: Thank you very much. It's
nice to be here. So, the story of this book,

00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:41.130
The Peep Diaries: How We're Learning to Love
Watching Ourselves and Our Neighbors, really

00:00:41.130 --> 00:00:53.210
starts about four years ago when I become
a father, and my social life starts to, you

00:00:53.210 --> 00:01:00.330
know, take a precipitous downturn. I used
to go out, and then all of a sudden I didn't

00:01:00.330 --> 00:01:07.220
go out. Any one who has had that experience
knows what I'm talking about. So social life

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:14.580
was diminished a lot of my "hipster" friends
who were no longer my friends, and this is

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:23.010
what things started to look like. Pretty much,
there's me, and that's me with my back hair.

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:29.380
There's the child. She does not yet have back
hair. She will hopefully take after her mother

00:01:29.380 --> 00:01:41.270
in that regard. So, yeah, basically, the social
life is diminishing to the point where I began

00:01:41.270 --> 00:01:47.740
to think that, really, I didn't have too many
friends, I start to wonder if I had any friends.

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:55.020
As, you know, you get more into the daddy
thing and everything just kind of changes.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:02:02.979
At the same time, I was starting to get into
things like Facebook, and Twitter, and these

00:02:02.979 --> 00:02:08.450
kinds of things which, you know, it all kind
of flirted with, you know, Friendster or whatever,

00:02:08.450 --> 00:02:16.930
but no one really got seriously into it. And
I was developing a lot of friends on that.

00:02:16.930 --> 00:02:24.779
That was my social life again. That was me
at the park. You can see, I'm looking happy,

00:02:24.779 --> 00:02:32.571
not. And like, where did my life go? Right,
so, I am basically, spending a lot of time

00:02:32.571 --> 00:02:38.919
at home with the kid, and I'm online a lot.
And, at one point, I noticed that, hey, you

00:02:38.919 --> 00:02:46.120
know, good old Hal has 700 friends on Facebook
but he doesn't actually have any friends in

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:54.330
real life. That's so sad. It's such a sad
life. So I had this genius idea which was

00:02:54.330 --> 00:03:01.120
that I would have a Facebook party, and I
would invite all my Facebook friends to come

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:08.169
and meet me at a local bar, and we would get
to know each other and I would, I would resuscitate

00:03:08.169 --> 00:03:14.930
my social life which is basically on complete
life support. And I needed to pull the wires

00:03:14.930 --> 00:03:20.200
out and like "zzzzzzzz" on Hal's social life
which was, you know, every time I left the

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:24.870
house, my wife was like, "Where are you going?
And where are you taking the baby?" So, okay,

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:31.010
so, I decided I'm going to have this Facebook
party, and I go ahead and I invite all, whatever,

00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:38.389
700 Facebook friends that I have at that time.
And I'll say, "You know, I want you to meet

00:03:38.389 --> 00:03:45.419
me at this local bar around the corner of
my house. I'm buying, come out, and we'll

00:03:45.419 --> 00:03:53.089
hang out." And I send this invitation note
and I got, I got a pretty good response, about

00:03:53.089 --> 00:04:00.489
30 people said they were may be coming, about
15 people said they were for sure coming,

00:04:00.489 --> 00:04:07.349
and, you know, a couple of hundred just said
no, and just ignored me. So, there I am, I'm

00:04:07.349 --> 00:04:12.559
at the bar. I've informed the bar that, you
know, I've got between 20 and 30 people coming

00:04:12.559 --> 00:04:18.169
to my Facebook party, and I'm ready for action.
See, I put my nice shirt on. I comb my hair.

00:04:18.169 --> 00:04:25.650
I shaved, just more than I can say. Now, I
just flew in from Chicago and I got all that--I

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:29.530
can't bring razors and shaving cream, and
everything. So I'm a little unkempt today.

00:04:29.530 --> 00:04:36.470
Joe, forgive me. So, I'm waiting for my friends
to show up, "Oh-oh, where are they?" No, no

00:04:36.470 --> 00:04:40.760
one showed up yet, it's getting dark. There's
me. As you can see, I have run through a few

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:47.930
beverages at this point, things are starting
to--I was starting to wonder what's going

00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:56.830
on exactly. So, no one's there. I'm waiting.
I'm waiting. And, oh, there we go. My Facebook

00:04:56.830 --> 00:05:00.370
friend is showing up Paula. Unfortunately,
she is the only the person who shows up to

00:05:00.370 --> 00:05:06.389
my Facebook party. So, only one person shows
up of the 700 invited. Paula, she's very sweet.

00:05:06.389 --> 00:05:13.240
She has a boyfriend. She plays some form of
sport which I forgot right now. She works

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:17.270
in customer service. She read one of my books,
thought it'd be nice to meet me. And, you

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:21.830
know, so we had this nice talk except that
I kept, like, kind of, apologizing from the

00:05:21.830 --> 00:05:26.740
fact that I invited her to a party, and, in
fact, I was the only member of the party.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:31.599
And I kept kind of looking over my shoulder
every time the door opens, praying that someone

00:05:31.599 --> 00:05:37.669
else would arrive to save us from this socially
awkward moment. But that never happened. Nobody

00:05:37.669 --> 00:05:42.949
else arrived, and it was just me and Paula,
and then Paula, you know, finished the drink

00:05:42.949 --> 00:05:51.599
that I bought her, and announced that she
was now going home. So, so that brought me

00:05:51.599 --> 00:05:58.190
to a kind of weird inspirational moment, if
you can call it like, "the inspirational moment."

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:06.000
There I am, Paula has left now. So I'm back
to drinking beer on my own. I'm an impressive

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:12.389
fellow. I can drink a lot of beer on my own.
Right. So, I had this, kind of, this moment

00:06:12.389 --> 00:06:16.960
where I began to think, you know, we're not
using these social networks for what we claim

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:22.340
we're using them for which is to meet people,
and connect and deepen our friendships, and

00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:27.580
make new friends. Then, what exactly are we
using them for, and--oh, there' me going home.

00:06:27.580 --> 00:06:31.759
There I am. I'm done. I [INDISTINCT]. They
threw me out of the bar. They were like, "Hal,

00:06:31.759 --> 00:06:38.909
no one else is coming." That's it. You're
out of there. Okay, so, I began to think that,

00:06:38.909 --> 00:06:44.289
in fact, most of us claim that we're using,
you know, Facebook, and other social network

00:06:44.289 --> 00:06:49.211
and sites to connect, to make friends, and
deepen friendship. But I began to think that,

00:06:49.211 --> 00:06:54.039
in fact, maybe we were also doing something
else which was basically, kind of watching

00:06:54.039 --> 00:07:00.090
each other, the way we watch television, sort
of, moving through people's lives. And I formulated

00:07:00.090 --> 00:07:07.710
this theory that we're moving from a pop culture
to a peep culture. And in pop culture, we

00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:13.740
derived our entertainment from watching celebrities
perform. And in peep culture, we are deriving

00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:18.270
our entertainment from watching people go
about their lives, go about their ordinary

00:07:18.270 --> 00:07:28.240
lives. And, obviously, the elements of peep
culture include things like, reality TV, like

00:07:28.240 --> 00:07:37.009
blogging, social networks, Facebook, Twitter,
YouTube. So, here, we have my little chart

00:07:37.009 --> 00:07:43.710
here, the pop versus peep chart. So, Pop:
Stars Have Talent. Peep: Who Needs Talent?

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:48.590
Pop: The Lives of Celebrities are interesting.
Peep: I'm Interesting And So Are you. Pop:

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:56.240
When Will They Discover Me? Peep: Too Late.
I've Already Discovered Myself. And, you know,

00:07:56.240 --> 00:08:00.139
it's kind of funny that this will--I guess,
this is going to be on YouTube, at some point,

00:08:00.139 --> 00:08:03.860
right. So, it's like all these clips I stole
from YouTube are going to go back on YouTube

00:08:03.860 --> 00:08:10.569
in some sort of twisted way. Okay. So, there's
three kind of peep culture that I've identified.

00:08:10.569 --> 00:08:17.449
We just saw--this is peeping ourselves. This
is, again, a video I took from YouTube, that

00:08:17.449 --> 00:08:23.029
is--this girl, and she talks about different
parts of her body as she goes through, and

00:08:23.029 --> 00:08:29.120
talks about her feet and her hands, and this
created a bunch of copycat videos, perhaps,

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:34.419
in the hundreds, maybe even the thousands
of similar talks of people showing different

00:08:34.419 --> 00:08:39.100
parts of their body, and discussing their
feelings about them. So, this is one kind

00:08:39.100 --> 00:08:47.830
of peeping ourselves, obviously, there are
many others. Again, you know, we have blogs.

00:08:47.830 --> 00:08:54.381
We have what we do in Facebook; we have the
information we put out on Twitter. We have

00:08:54.381 --> 00:09:01.670
all these different ways that we peep ourselves.
So here's a quote from Julie Allison who was

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:08.080
on the cover of Wire and sort of featured
as being one of the, the great--a kind of

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:17.391
Web 2.0 net celebrities. And she told Wire
about herself peeping, "I treat it like a

00:09:17.391 --> 00:09:21.700
fire. You have to add blogs, or there'll be
like one of those YouTube videos that flame

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:27.830
out." And after the article came out in Wire,
she wrote, you know, on her blog, "The irony,

00:09:27.830 --> 00:09:32.260
of course, is that publicity is a full-time
job. I did over two dozen print interviews

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:37.470
and 350 television segments in the last year.
I taught my brain to think in sound bites.

00:09:37.470 --> 00:09:42.480
In PR, nothing speak, to project authority
on subjects, I have no real knowledge about.

00:09:42.480 --> 00:09:46.730
It's a game that I'm a bit tired of playing
it. Now, I need to unlearn much of that."

00:09:46.730 --> 00:09:52.270
So, I thought that was a really interesting
observation on these whole phenomena of, kind

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:58.470
of, peeping yourself that you become really
involved in it, and it's kind of something

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:04.020
that becomes very hard to unlearn. So now,
we have peeping each other which is my, sort

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:09.100
of, second category of peep culture. Here,
this guy is going to walk over and you can't

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:12.441
really see the news--there's a newspaper at
the foot of the driveway, and he's going to

00:10:12.441 --> 00:10:16.100
walk over and he's going to kick the newspaper
behind that couch being put out for the garbage,

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:21.470
and he's going to bend off--bend down and
grab it and run away. Which, you know, it's

00:10:21.470 --> 00:10:25.600
amusing to watch in its own right, but what's
really interesting to me about this, of course,

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:32.330
is that the neighbor whose newspaper is being
stolen is filming this to put up on YouTube

00:10:32.330 --> 00:10:36.130
or wherever. So instead of maybe going out
and saying, "Hey, why are you stealing my

00:10:36.130 --> 00:10:40.940
newspaper? We have problem," we're peeping
each other. We're creating entertainment out

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:46.780
of these weird moments in life. This is the
naked wizard. He was wearing some sort of

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:53.660
wizard outfit before he decided to take it
off in a moment of--perhaps, incoherent, spontaneous

00:10:53.660 --> 00:10:59.230
happiness. Anyway, the police are eventually
going to wrestle him to the ground, handcuff

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:05.020
him and taser the shit out of him which is
unfortunate but not really the reason we're

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:12.170
watching this. As you can--you might notice,
as his situation intensifies more and more

00:11:12.170 --> 00:11:17.740
people gather around behind him and this is
at the Coachella Music Festival. So, more

00:11:17.740 --> 00:11:23.050
and more people are gathered around behind
him, and they're filming him. And the more

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:28.570
violent the situation gets, the more it escalates,
the more people are watching this, which again

00:11:28.570 --> 00:11:39.340
is, I think, a symptom of peep culture. It's
part of the way peep culture works that we

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:43.410
watch each other, we are peeping each other,
and then we sort of move away from getting

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:50.920
actually involved in situations in environments.
We just tend to sort of sit back and watch.

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:59.450
So then, there's this third category, Peeped
by 'The Other' which is this whole world of

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:07.070
search engines, corporations, different kinds
of entities that make--that facilitate peeping,

00:12:07.070 --> 00:12:13.080
that make it easy for people to peep on each
other, and do peeping themselves, obviously.

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:21.310
Google is part of that category. And this
is Pipl which, I don't know, some sort of

00:12:21.310 --> 00:12:27.680
Google rip-off, I guess, that does Pipl. Anyway,
I put my name into Pipl and it kind of provides

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:35.410
me with a list in categories of different
ways, different information you can find Hal

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:40.460
and I'm sure that there are people in this
room who can tell me how this works a lot

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:45.860
better than, I mean, I have no clue how it
works. But, all I know is the kind of social

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:50.570
effects of it. So there is some of the results
of when I put my name in. It's like every

00:12:50.570 --> 00:12:57.580
picture I've ever had put up on the Internet
comes up, all different links and blogs and--basically,

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:03.510
tons of information about Hal and it's neatly
ordered, so there's different, you know, categories

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:10.750
of find Hal, you know, locate Hal, various
variations on locating, finding, and accessing

00:13:10.750 --> 00:13:16.680
Hal. That's a lot of Hal. I don't know who
would ever want to do that. But--so this is

00:13:16.680 --> 00:13:23.730
the, this is kind of being peeped by the other
which is a kind of, peep culture facilitating

00:13:23.730 --> 00:13:31.100
of peep making it happen, collecting this
information, amalgamating it, organizing it.

00:13:31.100 --> 00:13:36.420
Here's another category of peeping by the
other. This is net detective obviously, you

00:13:36.420 --> 00:13:43.810
can go online, and I ordered net detective
search on my father for $34.95, I believe

00:13:43.810 --> 00:13:48.991
it was. I was going to do myself, but I live
in Canada, so they wanted $350, so I was like,

00:13:48.991 --> 00:13:57.350
"Fine, do dad." And, again, you get, a dossier
that's not that dissimilar from what you get

00:13:57.350 --> 00:14:03.840
on Pipl which is, kind of, just, you know,
everything that there is to know about my

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:09.890
father. It's a little bit more precise through
Net Detective. You get his mortgage; how much

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:15.980
he owes on the house; what income bracket
he's in; if he's retired or not; how many

00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:23.210
kids he has. All of these different categories,
and, you know, this is a sort of weird entertainment

00:14:23.210 --> 00:14:29.210
that we access, if we so choose. And this
is part of--this rise of peep culture that

00:14:29.210 --> 00:14:33.720
we can go and do these things for, you know,
they're pretty much the same costs as a movie

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:40.650
and popcorn. It was actually really funny
because when I got the net detective information,

00:14:40.650 --> 00:14:49.580
there's this one part that was like, criminal,
you know, criminal report. I was all excited.

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:52.492
I was like, "Now, I'm finally going to find
out the truth about dad." So I tear and open

00:14:52.492 --> 00:15:00.420
this piece of paper, and it's like speeding
ticket. Like, that was not, you know, that

00:15:00.420 --> 00:15:06.610
was not impressive for me. I thought, dad
maybe had like a third life or even a second

00:15:06.610 --> 00:15:14.380
life would've sufficed to make dad more interesting.
Come on, dad. Get going. Where is your fifth

00:15:14.380 --> 00:15:21.130
wife? And I don't know; your entire career
as a Canadian secret service agent. Anyway,

00:15:21.130 --> 00:15:28.940
okay, right, so in Peepville, we watch ourselves
and each other; it's what we do. Obviously,

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:34.550
in the book--I said I'm on this sort of quest
to understand why we're suddenly so interested

00:15:34.550 --> 00:15:40.590
in peeping; why we're moving from pop culture
to peep culture with such reckless abandon.

00:15:40.590 --> 00:15:49.500
So I start to explore some of the people who
do peep. This is, Lisa Sargese, who is a woman

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:56.751
who blogs, and video blogs about her life.
She started blogging about four years ago,

00:15:56.751 --> 00:16:02.760
I think, when she was about to have gastric
bypass surgery. She's morbidly obese, could

00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:09.900
barely kind of stand, and so she was going
in for the surgery, and right before that,

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:15.720
she started to seriously blog about her experiences.
So this is, obviously, someone who has been

00:16:15.720 --> 00:16:24.640
peeping herself very, very seriously over
the last four years. So I'll read a little

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:30.760
bit, this is from her blog, and she writes
on her blog, "My story doesn't matter, at

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:35.250
least, I don't think my story mattered until
folks started to thank me for sharing it.

00:16:35.250 --> 00:16:40.700
My fear, my low self-esteem, my aversion to
exposure and confrontation made me want to

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:46.310
hide. For years, I did hide. I hid behind
a mountain of fat. I'm still fat, at least,

00:16:46.310 --> 00:16:51.560
by society standards. No one takes into consideration
that I can walk from my classroom to my car

00:16:51.560 --> 00:16:56.120
without sitting three or four times. No one
looks at my big ass and applauds me for getting

00:16:56.120 --> 00:17:01.500
off it. No one is sympathizing with my impending
reconstructive surgery to cut off all the

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:07.810
inevitable loose skin. No one does until I
tell my story." And this is the video that

00:17:07.810 --> 00:17:13.830
she put up right after getting the surgery,
and you can see that she's really, you know,

00:17:13.830 --> 00:17:19.880
showing everything, not hiding anything. And
that's the video that's linked to her blog

00:17:19.880 --> 00:17:27.350
and up on YouTube. So, talking to Lisa made
me really realized just how kind of affirming

00:17:27.350 --> 00:17:32.780
peep culture can be, this idea of no one is
going to care about my story unless I tell

00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:37.410
it; unless I put it in front of people and
say, "Look at me. This is what I'm going through.

00:17:37.410 --> 00:17:43.070
You need to pay attention with my story."
At the same time, I noticed an evolution on

00:17:43.070 --> 00:17:48.860
her blog where she's kind of starts off wanting
to connect, wanting to tell her story, and

00:17:48.860 --> 00:17:53.020
hopefully, help other people. And then, as
she moves on, she becomes really, very focused

00:17:53.020 --> 00:17:59.300
on the idea that she has a following that
she is, perhaps, moving on to a career as

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:03.920
a kind of self-help guru. And so, later on
in her blog, I noticed a couple of years later,

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:10.250
she writes, "What is this drive I have to
be some bad ass, rock star celebrity. I don't

00:18:10.250 --> 00:18:16.730
know why I want more. I just do." So, she
very quickly, kind of, illustrates--I think,

00:18:16.730 --> 00:18:21.810
the addictive nature of peep culture, just
how much having some followers who are, who

00:18:21.810 --> 00:18:27.670
seem to be interested in the mundane details
of your life becomes a powerful feeling, an

00:18:27.670 --> 00:18:33.930
empowering feeling for you. And now, she really
talks about wanting to become the Oprah Winfrey

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:41.330
of, you know, people who go through gastric
bypass surgery. So another person I met who

00:18:41.330 --> 00:18:50.150
is in this category of seriously being a peep
participant, this is Amalyn. She does a video

00:18:50.150 --> 00:18:56.860
blog about her life, you saw her there, about
to have her, her daughter. And she started

00:18:56.860 --> 00:19:02.410
the blog right around that time, and she told
me that she was lonely and that she's a young

00:19:02.410 --> 00:19:07.390
woman and none of her friends were sharing
this experience with her 'cause they, of course,

00:19:07.390 --> 00:19:14.500
were off to college or whatever. It's not
very common for 20-year-olds now to have kids.

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:19.460
And she told me that her blog is a way for
her to reach out, and connect with people

00:19:19.460 --> 00:19:23.680
and, kind of, break out of her loneliness.
So I'm going to read you a quote. This is

00:19:23.680 --> 00:19:30.970
a discussion that ran alongside one of her
videos that she posted. And it was video talking

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:36.880
about her life that, in which she was wearing
a kind of shirt that was cropped like here.

