00:54:56.329 --> 00:54:58.219
'cause everybody caught it from different
angles on their camera that it pretty much

00:54:58.219 --> 00:55:03.710
like had them changed their policy or on shooting
and who was convicted and things like that?

00:55:03.710 --> 00:55:07.859
&gt;&gt; NIEDZVIECKI: Oh, absolutely, I mean, you
can't look at the phenomena of peep culture

00:55:07.859 --> 00:55:14.359
without looking at the political ramifications.
There's been all kinds of scenarios in countries

00:55:14.359 --> 00:55:23.400
all over the world where people abusing their
authority have been caught doing things, essentially,

00:55:23.400 --> 00:55:28.220
because of peep culture, because of this desire
to capture all these material. So when you

00:55:28.220 --> 00:55:31.880
look at it from that perspective, you'd say,
it's actually, kind of good. It's actually

00:55:31.880 --> 00:55:35.819
a good idea that we're all running around
with our cell phone cameras, because you'll

00:55:35.819 --> 00:55:42.700
never know when you're going to see these
abuses of authority. On the other hand, I

00:55:42.700 --> 00:55:48.309
think it's also fair to make the argument
that, you know, for every one time that you

00:55:48.309 --> 00:55:53.359
capture an abuse of authority, the other million
things that are being captured and posted

00:55:53.359 --> 00:56:03.819
